segments.text: Maxine was kind of, Maxine Davenport, Emanuel's then wife, was kind of den mother to the philosophy department.
And we all had parties.
Every weekend we had parties.
And they were lovely long parties where there was a lot of drinking going on.
And people brought their kids and they set them out in play pens under the trees.
And around six o'clock somebody would go out for fried chicken.
And sometimes a party would last from noon until two in the morning.
And we would talk about philosophical issues and literary issues as well as local things.
In fact, more than local things.
And so it was really a good time.
There were always, it was not just the ten of us, because each of these people had an attachment.
It was other people who were interested in philosophy.
I would say there would be about sixteen at each of these things.
And this went on for quite a while.
And many of them were interested in philosophy.
And Emanuel Davenport was very enthusiastic about kind of philosophy for ordinary people.
That was his shtick.
And so we would get in really good discussions in which everyone took part.
As opposed to now you get to a philosophy group and it's always very specialized, the discussion.
So people cannot participate unless they are, unless they know the language, walk the walk, talk the talk, and so forth.
It wasn't that way then.
It was open discussion.
Anybody who had an interest could easily get into the discussion.
Emanuel did interesting things.
For instance, he joined Mensa.
And then he suggested to Hugh that Hugh would be an appropriate member for Mensa, too.
And so I got irritated and I said, well, what about me?
I'm going to join this group, too.
So we went down to Austin to take the intelligence test, which was really goofy.
And we joined Mensa.
And then Emanuel had Mensa parties.
And these were really fun.
There would be a couple of Aggies, sometimes in uniform.
There would be some brilliant person who never had a chance to get out of a restrictive life.
There would be a handful of people from the university.
And these people would go over to his house and he'd provide refreshments and we'd talk about stuff.
So this was kind of when the philosophy department got a little bit tired of one another.
And this was a way of refreshing it.
But one thing I noticed is that he always had these chess sets and so forth set out so that anybody who wanted to can indulge in this kind of thing.
But nobody ever touched any of this stuff.
There were puzzles, chess sets.
People just talked.
And there was gossip, too, at these things.
I didn't think they were that much different from the regular philosophy parties.
But there was less alcohol because there were students.
I think we had beer.
And that was it.
But Emanuel always had some problems.
He always had some project.
He did a lot of work for the BCLU.
He was active in the Unitarian Church.
He was a wonderful auctioneer.
They were always auctioning stuff off for benefits.
And Emanuel was just great at that.
And so I remember those first few years actually in a kind of beery haze but very pleasant with Emanuel at the helm of the philosophy department.
Well, have you ever heard of him?
I've never heard of him.
I've never heard of him.
But he was a very good man.
He had a very good sense of humor.
And he was a very good man.
And he was very good at that.
He was a very good man.
And that's what I remember.
The reason I think that he was so good at that is because he was a very good captain.
He was a very good captain.
He was always a very good captain.
But the other thing I remember is that officially he was the department head.
Did he operate as a department head or department chair?
He operated as a department chair.
He did everything democratically.
And I believe that was an all Anglo male department, huh?
Yes, it was.
It was indeed.

This is a note to the typist.
This will go in as an editorial note.
I was dean of faculties at this time, and this is the last commencement that I attended
before going in the summer of 1980 to become the new president at the University of Texas.
At El Paso.
This is the last commencement in May of 1980.
We then had commencements on Friday afternoon, Friday night, and Saturday morning.
This is the Saturday morning commencement.
NM students then and now graduate in alphabetical order by college, by major, and by last name.
Melanie Zentgraf's undergraduate name.
Melanie Zentgraf's undergraduate major was biomedical science, which is the only undergraduate
major in the College of Veterinary Medicine.
So she was the last student, because of her last name, beginning with the letter Z, from
the last college, and that was the third commencement.
Her family, I learned later, had thought that we had deliberately rigged it so that she
would be the last of the last of the last.
That part is not true.
Our commencement speaker at that event was William P. Hobby, Jr., the lieutenant governor,
Bill Hobby, from Houston.
And while the diplomas are being passed out, Lieutenant Governor Hobby motioned to me to
come up from my seat on about three rows behind him and sit next to him, and he told me that
when I got out to UTEP to stay in contact, I should stay in contact with him, that he
would try to help me, since we didn't.
He would try to help me, since we'd known each other for about 20 years, and he said
such marvelous things as maybe I can help UTEP with a special item or something or other.
As I began to note that we were about to finish the commencement, I was starting to get up
from my seat and go back to the back row when I heard some hissing.
I turned to him and said, oh, my goodness.
He said, what is it?
I said, I don't know, but there are some people out there hissing, which means they're mad
about something, and particularly the corps members.
And I turned to my right, and I saw that Melanie Zentgraf was about to come up on the
stage, and I said, oh, my goodness, here comes Melanie Zentgraf.
He said, gee, Monique, she's really pestered me.
She's been a pain.
She's come over.
She's written letters.
She's madeMelanie's problem was that she had wanted to be on the fish drill team, in
the A&M band, in the Ross Volunteers, and for all three of those hopes, she had gotten
lame excuses.
And had been not allowed to compete for one of those positions.
The point of this editorial note is that within two or three feet of where I was seated, she
came up to receive her diploma.
President Jarvis Miller handed it to her.
She took it in her right hand, shifted it to her left hand, then extended her right
hand to him, and he very quietly said, no way.
I'm going to shake your hand.
The lieutenant governor and I and many, many people in the audience kind of held our breath
and gasped a bit.
She then turned to Bob Lacy, the registrar who was handing the diplomas to President
Miller, being sure that he handed the right diploma to him at the right time.
She extended her hand to Mr. Lacy, and Mr. Lacy said, ma'am, I'm not involved in this
argument.
She then turned to Don Carter, who was then on the staff of the registrar, and he said,
ma'am, let's keep the line moving.
So she went off stage, and being the last degree recipient, everyone noticed it.
Paragraph.
About six weeks later, when Dr. Miller was summoned over to a special meeting of the
Board of Regents, he walked in, and they announced to him that he had received the diploma.
He said that he had been terminated effective that day at 5 o'clock, that he had been terminated
as president.
They read him a statement, and the first thing I understand that they said to him on an ad
lib basis was, you refuse to shake hands with an Aggie graduate.

give every student at least the credit that they deserve.
